and I got diarrhea for a week.

292
00:14:45,759 --> 00:14:48,304
I know we don't pay a lot,
but this is a job,

293
00:14:48,387 --> 00:14:49,889
and we need to know we can count on you.

294
00:14:49,972 --> 00:14:52,349
We're meeting tonight
to discuss strategy for the--

295
00:14:52,433 --> 00:14:54,810
[Brittany] Dude, dude, dude...

296
00:14:54,894 --> 00:14:57,730
Oh, sorry to interrupt
whatever boring crap this is,

297
00:14:57,813 --> 00:14:59,648
but you need to get dressed.

298
00:14:59,732 --> 00:15:04,278
I got tickets to Taylor Splift,
the Taylor Swift reggae cover band.

299
00:15:04,361 --> 00:15:05,613
They're terrible.

300
00:15:05,696 --> 00:15:08,741
It's going to be amazing. [chuckles]
Hmm.

301
00:15:08,824 --> 00:15:10,743
Yeah, that sounds like more fun.
I'mma do that.

302
00:15:10,826 --> 00:15:12,620
-Eleanor!
-What?

303
00:15:12,703 --> 00:15:15,497
What? I've been nothing but good
for six months,

304
00:15:15,581 --> 00:15:18,792
and all I have to show for it
is this crummy apartment,

305
00:15:18,876 --> 00:15:21,629
a lawsuit, a loose caboose
and an overdrawn bank account.

306
00:15:21,712 --> 00:15:24,548
Being good is for suckers.
What do you even get out of it?

307
00:15:25,299 --> 00:15:28,177
A feeling of fulfillment in your soul.

308
00:15:30,512 --> 00:15:34,099
Gross. That's the grossest sentence
I've ever heard. Okay?

309
00:15:34,183 --> 00:15:36,852
I quit.
Eat my farts, Benedict Cumberbatch.

310
00:15:38,729 --> 00:15:41,231
Whew! I still think he's hot.

311
00:15:41,315 --> 00:15:44,193
I guess,
in a sick Victorian boy kind of way.

312
00:15:44,276 --> 00:15:46,403
Ooh, yeah. I want to feed him soup.

313
00:15:47,279 --> 00:15:48,781
[Eleanor] So tell me
about the new business.

314
00:15:48,864 --> 00:15:50,783
We sell classes
at a for-profit university,

315
00:15:50,866 --> 00:15:53,577
and the classes train people
how to sell supplements.

316
00:15:53,661 --> 00:15:56,205
So it's a Ponzi scheme
within a Ponzi scheme.

317
00:15:56,288 --> 00:15:58,457
-That sounds dicey.
-Oh, it's super dicey.

318
00:15:58,540 --> 00:16:00,417
But I'm in witness protection,
so, technically,

319
00:16:00,501 --> 00:16:02,461
I can't be convicted of any crime.

320
00:16:02,544 --> 00:16:04,838
That's definitely not true,
but I also don't care.

321
00:16:04,922 --> 00:16:06,173
Which one's my desk?

322
00:16:06,256 --> 00:16:07,800
[machines clacking]

323
00:16:09,093 --> 00:16:11,261
[sighs] You realize
what the problem is, right?

324
00:16:11,345 --> 00:16:13,013
But there's no way to help.

325
00:16:16,475 --> 00:16:17,768
[laughing]

326
00:16:17,851 --> 00:16:19,478
I'm only giving that guy three stars

327
00:16:19,561 --> 00:16:21,563
'cause he didn't let me stick my head
out the moon roof.

328
00:16:21,647 --> 00:16:24,525
Yeah! Dude, my boyfriend just texted.

329
00:16:24,608 --> 00:16:27,236
His wife's out of town,
so I'm gonna head over there. [kisses]

330
00:16:27,319 --> 00:16:28,862
What? That's lame.

331
00:16:28,946 --> 00:16:30,572
Boo!

332
00:16:30,656 --> 00:16:31,907
[Brittany] Happy birthday!

333
00:16:31,991 --> 00:16:35,536
Hello, bartender.
One alcohol drink, please.

334
00:16:35,619 --> 00:16:38,664
It's my birthday if you wanna
give it to me for free. [chuckles]

335
00:16:38,747 --> 00:16:42,001
I always say that,
but it actually is my birthday. [chuckles]

336
00:16:42,084 --> 00:16:44,753
Last year, on my birthday I almost died,

337
00:16:45,462 --> 00:16:51,301
and then I did a bunch of stuff
that was good, but weird,

338
00:16:51,385 --> 00:16:54,096
and then I stopped, and now I'm here.

339
00:16:55,055 --> 00:16:58,183
-Sounds like you had a pretty crazy year.
-Hmm.

340
00:16:58,767 --> 00:17:00,853
Want to talk about it?

341
00:17:01,562 --> 00:17:04,815
And in the end, Anthony Anderson
and Jerry O'Connell

342
00:17:04,898 --> 00:17:06,567
start a successful shampoo company,

343
00:17:06,650 --> 00:17:10,070
and you see the kangaroo
jumping around Australia.

344
00:17:10,154 --> 00:17:11,655
[laughing]

345
00:17:11,739 --> 00:17:15,784
That is the plot
to the movie <i>Kangaroo Jack. </i>

346
00:17:16,368 --> 00:17:18,787
-Why did I tell you that?
-It's unclear.

347
00:17:19,496 --> 00:17:23,500
You know, the thing is the problem
really with being a do-gooder?

348
00:17:24,084 --> 00:17:26,170
-What's that?
-No one cares.

349
00:17:26,253 --> 00:17:28,505
I mean, some people care a little bit.

350
00:17:28,589 --> 00:17:32,009
The twerpy little twerps
from the environmental place, they care,

351
00:17:32,092 --> 00:17:34,845
but I was a good person for six months.

352
00:17:35,512 --> 00:17:37,347
That's like five years.

353
00:17:37,431 --> 00:17:41,852
And it felt okay,
but not as good as I thought it would.

354
00:17:41,935 --> 00:17:44,354
And what did I get for it?

355
00:17:44,438 --> 00:17:47,524
Ah, see? Now you're talking
about moral dessert.

356
00:17:47,608 --> 00:17:48,609
Exactly.

357
00:17:49,943 --> 00:17:52,780
-Wait, I am? What?
-Moral dessert is the concept

358
00:17:52,863 --> 00:17:56,909
that if you act with virtue,
you deserve a reward.

359
00:17:56,992 --> 00:18:00,496
Right. If I'm not gonna get rewarded
somehow with a tiara

360
00:18:00,579 --> 00:18:03,457
or one of those diagonal award belts...

361
00:18:04,041 --> 00:18:04,958
-Sash.
-Sure.

362
00:18:05,042 --> 00:18:07,294
Then why should I do good things?

363
00:18:08,212 --> 00:18:12,341
You know, I had a friend that said
whenever she was doing something bad,

364
00:18:12,424 --> 00:18:15,260
she'd hear this little voice in her head.

365
00:18:15,344 --> 00:18:19,473
Distant little voice saying,
"Come on, now, you know this is wrong."

366
00:18:19,556 --> 00:18:22,768
And then when she started
doing good things,

367
00:18:22,851 --> 00:18:25,604
that voice went away. It was a relief.

368
00:18:26,188 --> 00:18:31,652
Your friend sounds like she's one pickle
short of a pickle party. [chuckles]

369
00:18:32,236 --> 00:18:36,824
She was a little rough around the edges,
but she was also a really good person.

370
00:18:36,907 --> 00:18:37,825
When she tried.

371
00:18:37,908 --> 00:18:41,286
See, I think that little voice
was her conscience

372
00:18:41,370 --> 00:18:43,872
trying to guide her
in the right direction.

373
00:18:45,457 --> 00:18:47,459
I gotta go home. What do I owe ya?

374
00:18:47,543 --> 00:18:49,169
The real question, Eleanor,

375
00:18:50,838 --> 00:18:52,256
is what do we owe to each other?

376
00:18:53,549 --> 00:18:57,302
What? Did I sell you a drink?
Am I a bartender?

377
00:18:57,386 --> 00:18:59,471
[chuckles] Drinks are on me.

378
00:19:00,514 --> 00:19:01,890
Good luck.

379
00:19:06,270 --> 00:19:07,604
Ow!

380
00:19:09,148 --> 00:19:10,649
[machines clacking]

381
00:19:12,776 --> 00:19:15,154
-Anybody notice I was gone?
-Nope.

382
00:19:19,158 --> 00:19:20,159
[laptop chimes]

383
00:19:33,922 --> 00:19:35,883
[Chidi through speakers]
<i>What do we owe to each other? </i>

384
00:19:35,966 --> 00:19:39,928
{\an8}<i>That is the question</i>
<i>Tim Scanlon asked decades ago,</i>

385
00:19:40,012 --> 00:19:44,266
{\an8}<i>and it is the question I will try </i>
<i>to answer over the next three hours.</i>

386
00:19:44,349 --> 00:19:45,851
{\an8}Ugh, no, thanks.

387
00:19:45,934 --> 00:19:47,936
{\an8}[Chidi] <i>We all have a voice in our head.</i>

388
00:19:48,020 --> 00:19:51,231
{\an8}<i>That voice doesn't tell us what to do</i>
<i>or not do,</i>

389
00:19:51,315 --> 00:19:53,483
{\an8}<i>but it does warn us </i>

390
00:19:53,567 --> 00:19:56,528
<i>when we do things</i>
<i>that don't feel good or right.</i>

391
00:19:56,612 --> 00:19:58,655
<i>The difference between...</i>
<i>...reasonable.</i>

392
00:19:58,739 --> 00:20:01,742
<i>What does it mean</i>
<i>to be a reasonable person?</i>

393
00:20:01,825 --> 00:20:03,577
<i>I may have a different definition</i>
<i>of reasonable...</i>

394
00:20:03,660 --> 00:20:04,995
<i>So why do it, then?</i>

395
00:20:05,078 --> 00:20:07,331
<i>Why choose to be good every day</i>

396
00:20:07,414 --> 00:20:10,584
<i>if there is no guaranteed reward</i>
<i>we can count on,</i>

397
00:20:10,667 --> 00:20:12,586
<i>now or in the afterlife?</i>

398
00:20:12,669 --> 00:20:16,548
<i>I argue that we choose to be good </i>
<i>because of our bonds with other people</i>

399
00:20:16,632 --> 00:20:20,302
<i>and our innate desire </i>
<i>to treat them with dignity. </i>

400
00:20:20,385 --> 00:20:23,013
<i>Simply put, we are not in this alone.</i>

401
00:20:25,432 --> 00:20:29,436
{\an8}Hi, dog bait. Didn't you get my message?
Let's go. Time is booze. [chuckles]

402
00:20:29,519 --> 00:20:34,650
{\an8}Yeah, no, thanks.
I'm going somewhere else.

403
00:20:40,197 --> 00:20:42,866
{\an8}-G'day, where you headed?
-Saint John's University, please.

404
00:20:42,950 --> 00:20:43,951
{\an8}No worries.

405
00:20:45,285 --> 00:20:47,162
{\an8}[machines clacking]

406
00:20:57,965 --> 00:21:00,592
-Hi.
-I'm sorry. Office hours are on Tuesday.

407
00:21:00,676 --> 00:21:04,596
Oh, I'm not a student.
Are you Chidi Ana... Kendrick?

408
00:21:04,680 --> 00:21:06,765
Anagonye. And, yes.

409
00:21:06,848 --> 00:21:09,810
From the long, nerdy video about
the voice that tells you to be good?

410
00:21:09,893 --> 00:21:11,603
From the Keswick Foundation lecture series

411
00:21:11,687 --> 00:21:14,439
on practical applications
of ethical theory, yes.

412
00:21:14,523 --> 00:21:17,067
Great. Hi, my name is Eleanor Shellstrop.

413
00:21:18,443 --> 00:21:19,444
Can we talk?

414
00:21:19,528 --> 00:21:21,196
[machines clacking]

415
00:21:22,364 --> 00:21:25,617
Okay. Here we go.
